nat columnates lists, like ls does with filenames. It reads its input from the
standard input, and takes the following options:

-d DELIM
	DELIM delimits input items. Newline by default.

-w WIDTH
	Output is WIDTH characters wide. Width of the terminal, $COLUMNS, or 80
	by default. -1 means one less than the default value.

-c COLS
	Output COLS columns. This option and -w are mutually exclusive.

-p PADDING
	Pad columns by PADDING spaces. 2 by default.

-a
	Fill rows instead of columns.

nat returns 0 on success, 1 if the number of output columns is not specified
and input is wider than the implied or specified output width, and 2 on error.

Example: displaying the largest packages on my system in columns:

$ dpkg-query -f '${Installed-Size}\t${Package}\n' -W '*' | sort -nr | cut -f2 |
 grep -v ^linux | head | nat -a
aocc-compiler-3.2.0      thunderbird       gcc-12     chromium    cpp-12       
openjdk-11-jre-headless  libreoffice-core  libllvm15  virtualbox  libllvm11    
$ 

See also:
* mc from Plan 9 <https://9p.io/sources/plan9/sys/src/cmd/mc.c>
* cols from sbase <http://git.suckless.org/sbase/file/cols.c.html>
